1) idk why you felt the need to post that in response to my completely unrelated ask for help about a combination other than seeing the word 'amphetamine' and having to chime in 2) the first study about striatum damage it cites one study that found damage in primates using non-comparable doses as those used in clinically in humans. this is acknowledged by the paper in question, so they attempt to use comparable doses. they then prove similar findings in reduced dopamine-specific neurology, but don't actually prove its due to striatal damage despite the literal title of the study. the biggest issue i find with this study is that they only followed up after cessation of treatment 2 weeks later, and didnt do long term analysis. it could very well be that the reductions in dopamine systems were temporary and due to higher levels of dopamine causing down-regulation, which is an entirely fucking normal homeostatic mechanism. i dont have sources, but as i recall, neurotoxicity with amphetamine and methamphetamine has only been proven in humans in recreational users who are partaking in enormous doses, and often combining it with other street drugs. i might be mixing this up with mdma, but honestly, i dont really care enough to go look for papers because this claim just seems like alarmist bullshit. 3) the third paper just says that amphetamine withdrawal causes depression. yes, it does. what's your point? many psychotropics that affect dopamine and serotonin cause temporary depression or rebound depression on cessation and withdrawal. this is due to the sudden steep decline in pre-synaptic NT levels. the brain is used to having a certain level of dopamine and serotonin. it takes time for the brain to adjust after this happens. people usually recover to a pre-treatment baseline after up-regulation occurs over the span of weeks or months. alasta 1/19/2022 5:42 PM
there are non-stimulant medications like straterra, and the weird one-off of wellbutrin that is technically not a stimulant but does release dopamine. clonidine has some success in the treatment of adhd but i dont fukken understand how. id think itd just act similarly to straterra in modulating epinephrine through alpha adrenergic action, and maybe some funky undiscovered MoA. you can also try methylphenidate if you can't adapt to the sleep disruptions, and aren't willing to use a sleep aid. it's less stronk than amphetamine, and people who have strong side effects from adderall et al often do well on it instead. it can also be combined with wellbutrin to synergize if it isn't enough by itself. there's also dexmethylphenidate, which is similar to dex-amp in being stronger than racemic mph caffeine is a stimulant, releasing a little bit of dopamine but mostly norepinephrine. as others have said, it synergizes well with l-theanine to improve attention over just caffeine alone, and also to reduce anxiety/stress/jitteriness. i got by on that combination for far too many years. there's also low-dose naltrexone, that causes dopamine release by very lightly antagonizing opioid receptors and confusing them into thinking something is wrong. LDN is v mild though. i use it as an adjunct to attenuate dopamine sensitivity. there's also L-tyrosine and methylfolate to increase available dopamine (since the former is a precursor and the latter supports NT synthesis in general)
